¿	Process vessel or pump releases due to cracks, or drain, bleed, or plug failure.

This scenario is considered in the EPA guidance document titled Model Risk Management Program and Plan for Ammonia Refrigeration dated May 1996 to represent a typical incident.  According to the EPA Guidance document, this canned scenario may be cited to fulfill the alternative scenario requirement.

¿	Vessel overfilling and spill, or over-pressurization, with rupture of vessel and/or venting through relief valves or rupture disks.


The compressor C-3 oil separator vessel has a 300 psig pressure relief valve venting outside the building with largest capacity pressure relief valve with the highest operating pressure.  This is a Hansen Relief valve rated at 63.8 lbs/min air at 300 psig.  Correction factor for air to ammonia is 0.6997.  Corrected release rate for ammonia is 63.8 lbs/min for 20 minute duration (distance to toxic endpoint is 0.1 mile);

The V-3 low temperature recirculator vessel shell rupture failure with an operating liquid level of 1,971 lbs at operating pressure of 0-5# psig.  With a vessel shell rupture failure with release rate of 221.84 lbs/min for 8.9 minute duration (due to the overall operating level of approximately 1,971 lbs. of ammonia as noted in the PSI information of the PSM Program, the total ammonia charge would be released within 8.9 minutes) distance to toxic endpoint is 0.1 mile;

¿	Shipping container mishandling and breakage or puncturing leading to a spill.

This scenario is not applicable to the facility.  Anhydrous ammonia is only received in bulk.  No shipping containers are used.

The facility has never experienced a significant release, therefore no release scenarios were considered. 
